XPS analysis was conducted to investigate the elemental compositions and chemical states of steel surfaces. As shown in Fig. 11
                           a and d, the peaks of Fe, O, Ca, and C were involved in the full-range XPS of both samples without and with CDs-based corrosion inhibitors. Whereas, the content of the O element was significantly reduced after adding CDs-based corrosion inhibitors (Table 4
                           ), revealing that CDs inhibited the corrosion process, thereby reducing corrosion products [63]. Notably, with the introduction of CDs, an evident N peak originating from CDs was detected, strongly verifying that multitudes of CDs adsorbed on the steel surface [34]. As disclosed in Fig. 11b and e, the high-resolution Fe 2p3/2 spectra contained four fitting peaks: Fe0 (705.5 eV), Fe2+ oxide (710.8 eV), Fe3+ oxide (709.2 eV), and Fe3+ hydroxide (711.9 eV) [64]. The high-resolution O1s spectra (Fig. 11c and f) could be divided into three peaks: O2− (528.8 eV), OH− (530.4 eV), and H2O (531.8 eV) [65]. Among them, O2− was related to iron oxides such as FeO and Fe2O3, OH− represented the production of FeOOH and Fe(OH)3, and H2O corresponded to the incorporated water molecules in the passive film. It is widely acknowledged that the Fe2+ species in the passive film exhibit superior corrosion resistance than the Fe3+ species [63,66–68]. As listed in Table 4, regarding the Fe2+/Fe3+ and OH−/O2− ratios calculated from XPS results, the specimen protected by CDs presented a higher Fe2+/Fe3+ ratio and a lower OH−/O2− ratio than the specimen immersion in Cl-SCPS without CDs. This finding drawn from XPS unveiled that CDs-based corrosion inhibitors could enhance the corrosion resistance of the passive film, thus providing effective protection against chloride corrosion [63].
